  "prompt": "Frontal lobe seizure?",
  "response": "A frontal lobe seizure is a type of focal seizure that originates in the frontal lobe of the brain. Here are key points:\n\nCharacteristics:\n- Often brief and complex\n- Can occur during sleep\n- May involve motor symptoms\n- Quick onset and termination\n\nSymptoms:\n- Sudden, involuntary movements\n- Abnormal body posturing\n- Bicycling or cycling-like leg movements\n- Rapid head and eye turning\n- Vocal sounds or screaming\n- Altered consciousness\n- Automatisms (repeated, purposeless movements)\n\nPotential Causes:\n- Genetic factors\n- Traumatic brain injury\n- Brain tumors\n- Stroke\n- Developmental malformations\n- Infection\n\nDiagnosis:\n- EEG (electroencephalogram)\n- Brain imaging (MRI, CT scan)\n- Detailed medical history\n- Video-EEG monitoring\n\nTreatment:\n- Anti-epileptic medications\n- Surgery (in some cases)\n- Lifestyle modifications\n- Identifying and treating underlying causes\n\nFrontal lobe seizures can significantly impact daily life and may be challenging to diagnose due to their complex and variable presentation.",
